      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Cheer for the Bronx</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Marilyn Seskin letter asks why tracts of vacant land in the Bronx are not being redeveloped for business (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Office Shortage Imperils Growth in New York City'' (front page, Sept. 19):</p>
        <p>The ideas that businesses entertain for more room to either expand or set up shop always include moving to Brooklyn, Queens or New Jersey. This raises a question that has plagued me. Why has there been no development of the Bronx?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Office Shortage Imperils Growth in New York City'' (front page, Sept. 19):</p>
        <p>The ideas that businesses entertain for more room to either expand or set up shop always include moving to Brooklyn, Queens or New Jersey. This raises a question that has plagued me. Why has there been no development of the Bronx?</p>
        <p>For decades vast lands lay vacant there waiting for business and residential development. It is not that far from Manhattan and subways already exist there for transportation. The last time I checked, it was still in New York City.</p>
        <p>MARILYN SESKIN  North Miami Beach, Fla.  Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
